CSS Selectors:
    Cascading Style Sheet
    Its is another way of locating elements on the web page
Syntax:
   tagname[attribute = 'attribute value']
   input[value = 'LOGIN']
   CSS dos not give us an opportunity to locate the elements by its text
Shortcut for CSS:
    Shortcut for the className --> "."
Syntax:
    tagname.classNameValue
    input.button
Shortcut for ID --> "#"
Syntax: tagname.#idvalue
        input#txtPassword
Contains() method in CSS:
    * symbol will represent contains method
    tagname[attribute *= 'partial attribute value']
    input[placeholder*='phone']
Starts-with method in SCC:
    ^(Circumflex) symbol represents starts-with method
    tagname[attribute ^= 'starting attribute value']
    input[aria-label ^= 'Pass']
ends-with method in CSS:
    $ symbol represents end-with method in CSS
    tagname[attribute $= 'ending attribute value']
    a[href $= 'login']
Xpath vs CSS:
    CSS cannot locate the elements by text whereas xpath can
    CSS has shortcuts
    Xpath doesn't have ends-with method
    CSS is faster then Xpath in locating elements
    CSS has more simple syntax then Xpath
WebElement Commands:
    Consists of several methods where we can perform an action and get the eklement state on the webpage

    isEnabled() - boolean
    isDisplayed() - boolean
    isSelected() - boolean
    clear() - void
    getTex() - String
    getAttribute() - String
    submit() - void


